The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A high court division bench on Friday asked civic commissioner Debashis Som to file an affidavit by May 13, elaborating the progress of the construction of a malaria hospital on Kalighat Road. The bench reacted sharply after Som told the court that the civic body had shelved the plan. He also submitted a report explaining the reasons for the move. 

 The court has asked you to go ahead with the work. Now, you will have to produce the progress report,? Chief Justice V.S. Sirpurkar, presiding judge of the bench, observed. The proceedings were part of the hearing on a petition filed by Pradip Roy, who has alleged that the civic body had backed out of its commitment to set up a malaria hospital.

 Flight services were disrupted on Friday because of technical problems and bad weather. Three airbuses of Deccan Air had to be grounded at Chennai airport because of technical problems. The airline?s Calcutta-Hyderabad flight, scheduled to leave at 7 pm, was cancelled. The Chennai-Calcutta-Chennai flight, scheduled to arrive at 6 pm, was delayed by several hours. 

 ccording to an airline spokesperson, Saturday?s Calcutta-Delhi flight (scheduled to leave at 10.25 am) and Calcutta-Hyderabad flight (in the evening) stand cancelled.

 Bangladesh Biman flight on the Dhaka-Calcutta route had to return to Dhaka after failing to land at Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose International Airport because of bad weather. It was scheduled to return late at night.

 US-based Starwood Capital Company plans to set up a hotel in Calcutta. A company delegation, led by managing director Jeffrey Eisenberg, met chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee on Friday morning. The group is seeking a seven-acre plot for the world-class luxury hotel. The company has stakes in several hotel chains across the world.

 The office of the state accountant-general on Friday launched the Interactive Voice Response System (IVRS), which will provide information about the general provident fund. Initially, the service will be available to all-India service officers and will be, subsequently, extended to state government employees.

 The high court on Friday rejected two petitions ? filed by Manju Sonkar and Swarna Kamal Saha ? challenging the validity of a notification of the state election commission on reservation of seats for the upcoming civic elections. Justice Soumitra Sen dismissed the petition after L.C. Behani, representing the poll panel, informed the court that the election process had already been initiated. 

 A fire broke out at a nationalised bank on NS Road on Friday morning. Fire brigade officials said the blaze was reported around 8.45 am. It was soon put out. Some equipment, including computers and fax machines, were destroyed. Around 20 years ago, a fire had razed the building.

 Brothers Jagjit and Manish Singh were seriously injured when the Ambassador they were travelling in rammed into a wall on Harish Mukherjee Road late on Thursday. Both were admitted to SSKM Hospital.

 A 50-year-old man was killed after a speeding vehicle knocked him down on Brabourne Road early on Friday. Police said the man was taken to Calcutta Medical College and Hospital, where he was pronounced dead. 

 TO Calcutta Park Street Ladies circle 46 for organising a sit-and-draw contest to raise funds for welfare projects




